50|$|The {{ship has}} {{undergone}} numerous refits {{since she was}} acquired by the Coast Guard in 1946. Sometime during the 1950s, Captain Carl Bowman replaced Eagles split spanker on the mizzenmast with a single sail. During the 1980s, under Captain David Wood, the split spanker was returned as it afforded reduced <b>weather</b> <b>helm</b> and allowed the helmsman to turn away (or 'fall off') from the wind more easily.|$|E
5000|$|The {{fundamental}} {{cause of}} [...] "helm", be it weather or lee, {{is the relationship}} of the center of pressure of the sail plan to the center of lateral resistance of the hull. If the center of pressure is astern of the center of lateral resistance, a <b>weather</b> <b>helm,</b> the tendency of the vessel to want to turn into the wind, or to weather-vane, will result.|$|E
