50|$|Sail twist is a {{phenomenon}} in sailing where {{the head of the}} sail is at a different angle of incidence from the foot of the sail in order to change the lift distribution with height. Twist is measured by comparing the angle of a straight line between the leading edge (luff) and trailing edge (leech) with that of the boom. Some twist is desirable, but too much can induce <b>weather</b> <b>helm</b> or ruin the slot between the mainsail and jib.|$|E
